filter()

Subset observatios based on their values.

5.2.4 Exercises

  1. Find all flights that
  • Had an arrival delay of two or more hours
filter(flights, arr_delay >=120)
  • Flew to Houston (IAH or HOU)
filter(flights, dest == "IAH" | dest == "HOU")
  • Were operated by United, American, or Delta
?flights

# tells me that there is another data frame with the two letter carrier abbreivation. See airlines to get the name.
airlines
# United == UA, American == AA, Delta == DL

filter(flights, carrier == "UA" | carrier =="AA" | carrier == "DL")
  • Departed in summer (July, August, and September)
filter(flights, month %in% c(7,8,9))
  • Arrived more than two hours late, but didnt leave late
filter(flights, arr_delay >= 120, dep_delay <=0)
  • Were delayed by at least an hour, but made up over 30 minutes in flight
filter(flights, dep_delay >= 60 & dep_delay - arr_delay > 30)
# if dep_delay = 60 and arr_delay is only 15, the flight made up 45 minutes

Departed between midnight and 6am (inclusive)

filter(flights, dep_time == 0)
filter(flights, dep_time == 2400)
filter(flights, dep_time <= 600 | dep_time == 2400)
  1. Another useful dplyr filtering helper is between(). What does it do? Can you use it to simpnlify the code needed to answer the previous challenges?
?between()

# between(x, left, right)

filter(flights, between(arr_delay, 120, Inf))
  1. How many flights have a missing dep_time? What other variables are missing? What might these rows represent?
filter(flights, is.na(dep_time))

# arr_time is missing; cancelled flights
  1. Why is NA ^ 0 not missing? Why is NA | TRUE not missing? Why is FALSE & NA not missing? Can you figure out the general rule? (NA * 0 is a tricky counterexample!)
NA^0
NA | TRUE
NA & FALSE
NA*0

arange()

arrange() works similarly to filter() except that instead of selecting rows, it changes their order. It takes a data frame and a set of column names (or more complicated expressions) to order by. If you provide more than one column name, each additional column will be used to break ties in the values of preceding columns:

5.3.1 Excercises

  1. How could you use arrange() to sort all missing values to the start? (Hint: use is.na()).
arrange(flights, desc(is.na(dep_time)))
  1. Sort flights to find the most delayed flights. Find the flights that left earliest.
arrange(flights, desc(arr_delay))
arrange(flights, dep_delay)
  1. Sort flights to find the fastest flights.
arrange(flights, air_time)
  1. Which flights travelled the longest? Which travelled the shortest?
arrange(flights, desc(distance))
arrange(flights, distance)

select()

5.4.1 Exercises

  1. Brainstorm as many ways as possible to select dep_time, dep_delay, arr_time, and arr_Delay from flights. (why?)

There are a number of helper functions you can use within select():
starts_with(abc): matches names that begin with abc. ends_with(xyz): matches names that end with xyz.
contains(ijk): matches names that contain ijk.
matches((.)\1): selects variables that match a regular expression. This one matches any variables that contain repeated characters. Youll learn more about regular expressions in strings.
num_range(x, 1:3) matches x1, x2 and x3.
See ?select for more details.

select(flights, contains("TIME"))
select(flights, contains("TIME", ignore.case = FALSE))

mutate()

mutate() always adds new columns at the end of your dataset so well start by creating a narrower dataset so we can see the new variables. Remember that when youre in RStudio, the easiest way to see all the columns is View().

5.5.2 Exercises

Working with the flights dataset (modular arithmetic)

time_test <- as.integer(2130)
time_test
[1] 2130
hour_int <- time_test %/% 100
hour_int
[1] 21
minute <- time_test %% 100
minute
[1] 30
minute / 60
[1] 0.5

Is there another way?

hour_trunc + minute/60

[1] 21.5
  1. Currently dep_time and sched_dep_time are convenient to look at, but hard to compute with because theyre not really continuous numbers. Convert them to a more convenient representation of number of minutes since midnight.

Walking through this step wise first make 517 -> 500

mutate(flights, dep_time_frac = trunc(dep_time/100)*100)

next confirm the fractional minutes

create the fractional minutes

mutate(flights, dep_time_frac = (dep_time - trunc(dep_time/100)*100)/60)

Now put the hour and fraction together

Repeat for the sched_dep_time

Make a new data frame with both variables

flights_frac <- mutate(flights, dep_time_frac = trunc(dep_time/100) + (dep_time - trunc(dep_time/100)*100)/60,sched_dep_time_frac = trunc(sched_dep_time/100) + (sched_dep_time - trunc(sched_dep_time/100)*100)/60)
flights_frac
